snippet.textDisplay: Have you ever looked at the ingredients in that meat substitute?  Outside of getting this as a vegan I don't understand why someone would order it. It's more processed than traditional ground beef, and nowhere near as healthy. 85/15 ground beef has 100 few calories, 2g more protein, and 340mg less sodium (400mg of sodium for one serving is crazy).  No one whoever gripes about eating "processed food" should ever go anywhere NEAR this stuff, because it is totally made up of chemicals and substances that have been subjected to chemical and mechanical processes that reduce the original substances to nothing that remotely approaches a "natural" state. There is nothing natural about this. If you refuse to eat real meat for other than allergic reasons, then you should not want anything that resembles meat, tastes like meat, feels like meat in your mouth, or cooks like meat.

snippet.textDisplay:
I did it to them.  

Thank you for showcasing vegan recipes. You and Jenna sharing your kitchen proved to me that going vegan is actually super easy. And flavorful! I'm going on 3 years all veg 24/7.

I made it with the Italian version of that beyond meat sausage versus the bratwurst flavor that you used, which I think added too much spice. Overall good, but I want to work on this recipe again. My hominy didn't really "pop" despite simmering for 2.5 hours. Comparing this soup to my tortilla soup recipe adapted from Dona Thomas cookbook which takes less time, I'd give 8 out of 10, like anyone cares.
snippet.textOriginal:
I did it to them.  

Thank you for showcasing vegan recipes. You and Jenna sharing your kitchen proved to me that going vegan is actually super easy. And flavorful!  I'm going on 3 years all veg 24/7. 

I made it with the Italian version of that beyond meat sausage versus the bratwurst flavor that you used, which I think added too much spice. Overall good, but I want to work on this recipe again. My hominy didn't really "pop" despite simmering for 2.5 hours. Comparing this soup to my tortilla soup recipe adapted from Dona Thomas cookbook which takes less time, I'd give 8 out of 10, like anyone cares.

As a mexican, that looks amazing !! (I was a little worried at first ngl)
Some pro-tips to enjoy future pozoles: tostadas have more flavor than tortillas, lettuce is better than cabbage imo, and you can add a little oregano at the end or some chili powder (to your bowl) to add more flavor (as you did with lime, it's so good right?), and if you can handle it... add MORE chile/adobo to the soup oh yeah <3

snippet.textDisplay:
Okay I have an idea. I’m from the Netherlands and we’re known for our traditional and nutritious foods. There’s this meal called ‘andijviestamppot’ and it’s made out of endive and potatoes. I don’t know if they sell endives in the US, but if they do anywhere it should be in LA. It’s a very old Dutch meal and I haven’t seen it in any other country. Since Julian is vegan, I looked up a vegan recipe (in the original recipe there’s bacon bits and milk) and I believe this one might work. It’s a Dutch recipe though so I translated it for you lol:

Ingredients:
6 organic and medium sized potatoes • 1 head of endive · 2 red onions (small) · 2 cloves of garlic • a dash of oat milk • 1 tablespoon of coconut oil • 1 tablespoon of turmeric • pinch of Himalayan salt

PREPARATION
1. Peel the potatoes and cut them in half. If you have little time, you can also cut them into small cubes, then the cooking time will be less long. Heat water in a large pan and bring it to the boil with a pinch of Himalayan salt.
2.When the water is warm, put the potatoes in and boil them for about eight minutes until you can pierce the potatoes with a fork.
3. Drain the water and add the dash of oat milk, coconut oil and turmeric. Mix this together until you have potato puree.
4. Cut the endive into small pieces and wash it well. Add this to the mashed potatoes and stir well together.
5. Fry the garlic and the onions briefly and decorate your endive mash with it.
If you want to you could add pieces of pork substitute to mimic the original recipe.

Do with this information what you will but I think this might make for a fun video idea :)
